<Review ID>4116856
<Product Name>SanDisk Sansa View 16 GB Video MP3 Player (Black)
<Title>Okay for audio doesn't play video properly
<Date>Thu Jan 03 00:00:00 CST 2008
<Content>I have a lot of experience with these devices.   Ipod Video units, Creative Vision M, other sansa players.  The good: this player is smaller and lighter than Hard Drive based players, it is expandable too, with micro SD Flash RAM.   You can drag and drop to and from it.    Not tied to itunes or other software.   You can use it with rental music stores like Napster (requires use of WMP).   It can hold a lot of material, especially for a flash based player.   It is affordable and simple to use.  The bad: the interface is not near as smooth as the ipod, Contrary to specification it will not play back my video files that the ipod will, this player locks up especially with longer videos.   I have encoded them properly at 320x240.    In addition it lacks the capacity to play 640x480 files (not supposed to to but would have been nice).   So it is really just a higher capacity larger form factor sansa MP3 player.    Too many issues with video to be worth while as PVP.   The rewriting of the database when you unplug it is slow.  That said Apple's new IPODS have been engineered with a new piece of firmware that cripples video unless you use their new docks that have an authentication chip in them.    I would recommend boycotting apple ipod products until they release firmware that no longer locks out third party cables and docks.   They did this without warning so an IPOD classic for example is not an actual classic because the ipod video units that it replaces work well with third party cables and docks and the Classic is designed not to!  So I will end up stuck with the Sansa because I got it for xmas and it was over the 30 day period when I received it and found the video issues but I am not happy with it.    My players of choice remain the Gen 5 and 5.5 Ipod Video units, they are not designed to allow moving music and video on and off like the View allows but they do work and with third party software you can transfer music and video from them to you computer.  I would not recommend the ipod nano because even though it plays video they put that same authentication chip in it.   Yes the View may not have a video out capability at this time, but at least Sandisk didn't purposely engineer firmware so you can't use older Sansa docks or third party products with it.      
<Overall>2

<Review ID>1276785
<Product Name>SanDisk Sansa View 16 GB Video MP3 Player (Black)
<Title>Looks great, decent interface, but terrible hardware and sofware.
<Date>Fri Jan 04 00:00:00 CST 2008
<Content>I was really excited when I got my Sansa View. I'm a SanDisk fanboy. In the past SanDisk has proven themselves a very reliable company with solid products. As soon as I had my songs loaded up and began skipping through them I noticed my Sansa View began locking up, remaining unresponsive until I turned it off.   This was a big let-down as I was very happy to have a flash-based MP3 player with this kind of storage and advertised battery life. The battery life was not even close to the claimed 37 hours of music. After fully charging my Sansa it was down to half power after a few hours. The radio reception and audio recording were pretty poor in quality too. I'm returning mine as soon as I can. I'm not sure why this is getting such positive reviews, but my experience was not good. I haven't had an MP3 player this bad since I made the horrible mistake of buying a Sony.  This was a huge disappointment with me, my old 2gb Sansa worked great. SanDisk really dropped the ball on this one.  
<Overall>1

