<Review ID>2326631
<Product Name>SanDisk Sansa View 16 GB Video MP3 Player (Black)
<Title>Best bang for your buck .mp3 player as of Jan. 2008
<Date>Sat Jan 12 00:00:00 CST 2008
<Content>This is basically a refined and supersized version of SanDisk's e200 series .mp3 players, which were already pretty good.  I've had mine for about 2 weeks, here are some of my thoughts on it:  -Only thing I really miss is the tactile feed back (it clicked when you moved it) from the old selector wheel, but they've compensated for it somewhat by requiring you to move the wheel a bit more to highlight a selection.    -Make sure you update the firmware ASAP, its still very new so the default firmware has bugs, they've been quick to fix them though.  -Almost no accessories out for it at the time of this review.  Somewhat annoying as this thing attracts scratches as much as it attracts fingerprints, you definitely want to get one for it if you want to make sure it doesn't look beat up within a year.  I got the generic black silicone one that you see here:  http://www.overstock.com/Electronics/Sandisk-Sansa-View-Silicone-Skin-Case-with-Armband/2916955/product.html, it protects the case quite well and doesn't block the buttons but doesn't protect the screen at all.  -Its bigger than the e200 series but its not huge by any means, actually fits in my pocket a bit better since its thinner than the e200 series was.  -It can play movies but don't bother getting it for that (I'd look at a Archos or something similar if you want to view your movies while you wait on a plane or something), the screen is still to small and it eats up the battery time quickly, this is still first and foremost a .mp3 player.  -Transfer speeds are fine, it took 20 min. or so to move about 3.8GB of .mp3's to the View.  Someone was complaining about how slow it was to move files despite having a USB 2.0 interface in one of these reviews, thats a common issue with flash right now. Its very durable and uses less power than a mechanical micro hard drive but it also has slower read and write speeds, so no matter how fast that USB 2.0 interface is it can only move data around as fast as the flash memory will allow it to.  Its a trade off that is well worth it IMO, especially if go running with it.  -You can move files/.mp3's to and off it just like the e200 series by treating it like a USB flash drive, no crappy media transfer software required!  However you have to put the View into MSC mode to do it first, note that protected (DRM'ed files, like Amazon Unbox, iTunes, etc.) files will not work, also it will mess up your .mp3 playlists if you go back and forth between MSC and MTP (they may fix this though with a firmware update...).  There is a "secret handshake" you have to do to get into this mode:  # Put the View into hold.  # Hold down the Left button (left side of the jogwheel) for about 10 seconds. You will see the screen black out for a second and then come back.  # Connect the View to the PC.  It'll show up as a regular flash drive (as will the microSD slot) in My Computer on winXP.  -You can't switch out the battery yourself like you could with the e200 series but the one that is built in should last a long time so long as you charge it properly.  
<Overall>5

<Review ID>3434335
<Product Name>SanDisk Sansa View 16 GB Video MP3 Player (Black)
<Title>Great Possibilities, Horrible Quality
<Date>Sun Jan 13 00:00:00 CST 2008
<Content>If you are impatient and can't read the following...long story short...this product is of terrible quality and is cheaply made.  I had researched both this product and the creative Zen 16 gig player throughly prior to purchase and decided on the Sansa View because of its better SD card integration, superior battery life, compatibility, and user interface.  However when I received my product I immediately notice that the face plate was off center and there was a prominent overhang of a few millimeters that over time would most definitely result in the faceplate coming off the unit.  I called Sandisk and they gave me difficulty with an RMA so I decided to exchange it at BestBuy.  BestBuy, to my complete suprise, was actually very helpful exchanging the product and opening it up to ensure that I would be satisfied with the new one.  When they opened the box however we found that there was an actual crack running along the faceplate seal and you could see into the player.  Because that product was unsellable they opened up yet another Sansa View.  This time the faceplate was more or less centered but again it had a visible crack.  Although this crack was smaller it most certainly will grow over time until it splits open.  Clearly this is a quality issue on Sandisk's part as three out of three units had obvious defects.  Now I'm stuck with a unit that is going to break open in a matter of months.  Keep in mind Sandisk doesn't cover cracks in the faceplate because they will claim it is due to normal wear and tear.  Bottom line:  great potential as a product, terrible quality, don't expect it to last, buy at your own risk.  
<Overall>2

<Review ID>4203808
<Product Name>SanDisk Sansa View 16 GB Video MP3 Player (Black)
<Title>I had an e260, now I have this
<Date>Sun Jan 13 00:00:00 CST 2008
<Content>So to anyone that owned the previous e200 product, this review might be interesting to you. Here are some things that they fixed form the e200.  -The record "feature" on the side of the unit is now a slider button and I have never hit it accidentally unlike on the e200.  -The wheel is much higher quality and it is also a "click wheel" so you don't have to deal with the tiny buttons around the wheel like on the e200. -Video is no longer .mov (yuck) so I think that opens more opportunities.  -It starts up MUCH faster!  Here are some things they didn't fix! -The volume levels are still all wrong to me. There is still a "normal" and "high" volume mode. Couldn't they just make the volume scale better?  -The player still randomly freezes. It freezes reliably for me when I do "recent tracks" or "play all tracks" and then skip through some songs. Hopefully they will fix this in a firmware release. -Sansa Media Converter 2 sucks about as bad as Sansa Media Converter 1.   And in general: -The battery life on my View is very unimpressive. I haven't been getting more than 4 or 5 hours if I had to guess. It's rated at 35! I might send mine in but that means I get a refurb back...blah -There have been some reviews that say the low end sound is a little flat. I haven't really noticed but I don't listen on high quality headphones or high quality car audio system.  -It should get louder even on the "high" volume setting, and it should get lower even on the "normal" volume setting.  -Why the need for a proprietary USB connector?? -The video feature is cool I guess, and it was something I thought about when I bought it, but just like on my e260 -- I never use it. You might want to be realistic with yourself if you're choosing it thinking you will use the video feature...  Overall it works really well as an audio player. If I didn't have a battery issue i would give it a 4.   
<Overall>3

<Review ID>2674510
<Product Name>SanDisk Sansa View 16 GB Video MP3 Player (Black)
<Title>If you want to play Audible Books, don't buy
<Date>Thu Jan 17 00:00:00 CST 2008
<Content>Having had much success with previous SanDisk products using Audible I purchased the 16GB View.  However, much to my disappointment, I found using the View for Audible unacceptable.  If, after listening to part of a book, you switch to a song or another book, and then return to the original book, the book starts all over again.  I contacted Audible who referred me to SanDisk who informed me that the device was designed that way.  Very disappointing to say the least.  Who wants to fast forward every time after returning to a book?  For full disclosure, the device does start up where you left off on a book if you power down; but if you at any time, while the power is on, switch to another song or book, you start all over on the original book.  This is not acceptable and the device is being returned ASAP!  
<Overall>2

<Review ID>0539986
<Product Name>SanDisk Sansa View 16 GB Video MP3 Player (Black)
<Title>iPod or Zune?  How about neither?
<Date>Sat Jan 19 00:00:00 CST 2008
<Content>For months I struggled with the decision of where to put my money on an mp3 player.  The search ended here and I'm quite happy with it.  Primarily, I didn't want to be handcuffed to iTunes or Zune's market place.  Another concern was the conversion of mp3 and .wma files.  Also I didn't want to have to deal with DRM music or additional software on my PC to learn or navigate.    This device does it all: music, video and pictures, plus it even has an FM tuner.  It syncs up through Windows Media Player's library and does a nice job.  I have over 2000 songs (and now growing) and the Sansa View loads in about one hour through a USB connection.  If I run out of room I can add a micro SD card for about $80.  If you're worried about disk space, spend another $100 and go for the Sansa View 32.  Get the extended warranty (two years) just in case.  For about $30 it's good insurance.  It's slim, lightweight and very intuitive to use.  I have called Sandisk's tech support once for assistance and they were quick to answer, professional, and they spoke English.  My friends who have other brands see it and they all are impressed with it.  Honestly, you can't go wrong with this one.  
<Overall>4

