<Review ID>5590781
<Product Name>SanDisk Sansa View 16 GB Video MP3 Player (Black)
<Title>Big hopes. Horrible experience.
<Date>Wed Dec 26 00:00:00 CST 2007
<Content>For Christmas I decided that it would be time to officially launch myself into the world of portable MP3 enjoyment. Although my audio collection was quite extensive I always played my music selections from a desktop or laptop system, but it finally seemed time to enable my enjoyment of the media while "on the go". I began my research into the available MP3 players in early November, and after a few weeks I finally settled on the Sandisk Sansa View 16GB model. I was greatly pleased by the model's price-to-capacity ratio, and my experience with an 8GB display model in Best Buy was brief but enjoyable.  I wrote out my letter to Santa making sure to detail my good deeds for the year while playing down my less-than-admirable actions and eagerly awaited Christmas morning. You can imagine my joy to find the nice little package patiently awaiting my unwrapping that morning, and in no time I had the device unpackaged and juicing itself up to full charge via my laptop while we visited my relatives for the day's festivities.  At the end of the day I returned home to find the device mysteriously off even though the USB charging cable was still plugged in and the laptop still dutifully chugging away. This is where my troubles began, but let me start by listing the positives of this device:  The Good: * The Sansa View interface is intuitive and responsive. * The support for the USB Mass Storage class is appreciated. * The size to capacity ratio is currently unbeatable in the flash-based MP3 player market. * The integrated FM tuner is a major plus.  The good is why I purchased this device, and these points were all addressed in early reviews of the relatively new product. However, I have to question if the reviewers were given either incomplete prototypes or were given units which were specifically tested to function for the reviewers. Having thoroughly digressed now I return to the Christmas evening in question.  I pickup up the device to find the screen was on but blank and the controls were completely unresponsive - not a good sign. The device had apparently locked up. After some research I found how to hard shut down the device so I unplugged and rebooted the device. I confirmed that the device was indeed fully charged, so I once again plugged the device back into my laptop in order to transfer music. That's when strange things started happening again.  The device continuously rebooted itself while plugged in, but not knowing the particulars of the device's transfer methodology I let it sit until 10 minutes later when the device was finally recognized by my laptop and stopped rebooting. I browsed the device to the music folder and began copying over a sample 5GB of music to the device and observed very strange behavior. Although the device and my laptop are USB 2.0 compatible the transfer took roughly 30 minutes - far longer than acceptable for the USB 2.0 protocol. I tried on different ports to eliminate the possibility of a fried USB port on my laptop but observed the same behavior. Strangely enough the, device seemed to mirror it original connection issue as it appeared to lose and reestablish the USB connection repeatedly during the transfer which possibly caused the great delay in the data transfer. Strike one.  Once the transfer finally completed I had to reboot the device again as it had once again locked up, but once the database was rebuilt within the player all my music was there and I tried to enjoy the fruits of my labor by playing some music - you know, the reason the device was created in the first place. However, every single MP3 that I played in various formats - WAV, ACC, and MP3 (various encoding engines and bitrates) caused the device to crash after ~20s-30s of playback requiring a hard reboot. So the device is more or less unusable. Strike two.  I figured that since the device was relatively new that maybe there were a few bugs that needed to be worked out and may have already been addressed in new firmware updates. I browsed the Sandisk website to find that they did not offer updates for download, and only through the kindness of a forum member was I able to get the new update. But alas, t'was for naught. I needed to copy the firmware update to the device and reboot it to apply the update but at this point no matter which computer I plugged the device into no computer recognized the device. I could not apply the update which means I was basically out of luck completely. Strike three.  While browsing the basically user-run support forum I was alerted to an issue that I had previously not noticed - The device was split along the left side of the case! I could actually see into the device, and I could surmise that this defect would only grow through normal wear and tear. Strike four - you're very out.  I continued to attempt to get the device to work on various system and operating systems (Windows XP, Suse Linux 10.2, FreeBSD 5.0) but the behavior was the same on all systems. At this point I was now eight hours into the frustrating ordeal and begrudgingly packed up the device into its store packaging for a prompt refund. The sad part is that I really wanted to like this device - its features were outstanding. However, features are good and well but when they don't work it's kind of a moot point.  I am an Electrical Engineer by degree and a Computer Programmer by trade, and I can assure you that if my team released a product of this quality there would be one or more people left without a job.  Sorry Sandisk - You make great memory cards but I don't foresee myself ever purchasing an MP3 player again considering my experiences have bee mirrored by numerous other users on various forums.  
<Overall>1

